{"key":"post-13051230","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13051230</id>\n<content>First, that's not a valid method of pasteurization.&amp;nbsp; You want to hydrate the substrate and then heat it to 140F to 160F for an hour, being careful to stay below 160F.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Second, don't scoop spawn out with a spoon.&amp;nbsp; Bang the jar against a tire or phone book, etc., to break up the grains.&amp;nbsp; Then, you can pour them out like sand.&amp;nbsp; The spoon cuts some of the grains in half, exposing uncolonized parts to contaminants.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Third, 80F is too hot for bulk substrates.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium will heat up at least ten degrees, and 90F is WAY too hot.&amp;nbsp; This is also the reason for your condensation.&amp;nbsp; It's warmer on the inside of the tub than the 80F on the outside.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Generally, when a substrate contaminates prior to first flush, it's the spawn at fault.&amp;nbsp; I suspect the biggest culprit is using the spoon, sterilized or not.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13051258</next>\n<prev>13051154</prev>\n<first>13051154</first>\n<last>13051377</last>\n<when>1281822433</when>\n<utime>08/15/10 12:47 AM</utime>\n</post>"}